  </h1>
  <h2>Hello and welcome! ðŸ‘‹</h2>
  <p>
    Thanks for visiting this about page and I hope you have enjoyed my app! I
    created this project while I was brushing up on my backend skills with
    NodeJS and Express.
  </p>
  <p>Sometimes I like to check it before I get dressed for the day.</p>
  <figure>
    <img
      class="scout-picture"
      src="/scout-snow.jpg"
      alt="picture of scout in snow with jacket on"
    />
    <figcaption>I should have worn my mittens..</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    This is the first project I have completed from scratch using
    <a class="link" href="https://nodejs.org/en/">NodeJS</a>,
    <a class="link" href="https://expressjs.com/">ExpressJS</a> and
    <a class="link" href="https://ejs.co/">EJS</a> templating on the backend. It
    uses the free openweathermap.org API to get the
    <a class="link" href="https://openweathermap.org/current"
      >current weather</a
    >
    via a US zip code. The GET request then uses the response data to gather the
    longitude and latitude of the city (they are printed at the bottom of the
    results pages).
  </p>
  <figure>
    <a
      href="https://openweathermap.org/api"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer"
      ><img
        id="owapi-screen"
        src="/openweatherscreen.jpg"
        alt="open weather api screenshot"
        width="900"
    /></a>
  </figure>
  <figcaption>
    Openweather.org offers multiple free API calls to fetch data with.
  </figcaption>
  <p>
    That longitude and latitude are then used for a more advanced
    <a
      class="link"
      href="https://openweathermap.org/api/one-call-api"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer"
      >ONE CALL</a
    >
    API call. This response holds a large amount of information including:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>hourly and minutely data</li>
    <li>temperatures</li>
    <li>wind</li>
    <li>rainfall</li>
    <li>cloud cover</li>
    <li>sunrise and sunset</li>
    <li>weather alerts</li>
    <li>and more...</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    After we have the data, we can then pass it to different template 'views'
    using EJS. This process has it's pros (it saves time using templates and
    variables like they are components and props in React) and cons (you cannot
    access the DOM elements or events directly since the 'views' don't get
    rendered on the server, but on the browser).
  </p>
  <figure>
    <img
      class="scout-picture"
      src="/scout-hat.jpg"
      alt="picture of scout with hat on"
    />
    <figcaption>Today is definitely going to be hat weather.</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <p>
    Overall, it was great practice using EJS templating engine and, as always,
    the
    <a
      class="link"
      href="https://openweathermap.org/api"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer"
      >openweathermap.org</a
    >
    api is an amazing and powerful free tool and I would recommend any new
    developer to check it out.
  </p>

